TITLE = "Mean (Arithmetic Average)"

SECTIONS = [
    {
        "title": "What is the Mean?",
        "body": '<h3>Mean is the Most Common Average</h3><p>The <strong>mean</strong> is the type of average we calculate by adding all values and dividing by how many values there are.</p><div class="concept-box"><strong>Mean \(= \text{Sum of all values} \div \text{Number of values}\)</strong></div><p>The mean is used in many real-world situations:</p><ul><li>Average temperature each day</li><li>Average score in a test</li><li>Average height of students in a class</li><li>Average pocket money received</li></ul>'
    },
    {
        "title": "Calculating the Mean Step-by-Step",
        "body": '<h3>Three Simple Steps</h3><ol><li><strong>Add</strong> all the values together (find the sum)</li><li><strong>Count</strong> how many values there are</li><li><strong>Divide</strong> the sum by the count</li></ol><h3>Example 1: Simple Numbers</h3><div class="worked-example"><p><strong>Find the mean of: 12, 15, 18, 21, 24</strong></p><ul><li>Step 1: Sum = \(12 + 15 + 18 + 21 + 24 = 90\)</li><li>Step 2: Count = 5 numbers</li><li>Step 3: Mean = \(90 \div 5 =\) <strong>18</strong></li></ul></div><h3>Example 2: Test Scores</h3><div class="worked-example"><p><strong>Find the mean of test scores: 85, 92, 78, 88, 95</strong></p><ul><li>Step 1: Sum = \(85 + 92 + 78 + 88 + 95 = 438\)</li><li>Step 2: Count = 5 tests</li><li>Step 3: Mean = \(438 \div 5 =\) <strong>87.6</strong></li></ul></div>'
    },
    {
        "title": "Mean with Decimals",
        "body": '<h3>When the Mean is Not a Whole Number</h3><p>Sometimes when we divide, we get a decimal. That is fine!</p><div class="worked-example"><p><strong>Find the mean of: 2.5, 3.2, 4.1, 2.8</strong></p><ul><li>Step 1: Sum = \(2.5 + 3.2 + 4.1 + 2.8 = 12.6\)</li><li>Step 2: Count = 4</li><li>Step 3: Mean = \(12.6 \div 4 =\) <strong>3.15</strong></li></ul></div><h3>Example with Money</h3><div class="worked-example"><p><strong>Four friends spent: £8, £12, £15, £10 on lunch. What was the average spending per person?</strong></p><ul><li>Step 1: Sum = £8 + £12 + £15 + £10 = £45</li><li>Step 2: Count = 4 friends</li><li>Step 3: Mean = \(£45 \div 4 =\) <strong>£11.25</strong> per person</li></ul></div>'
    },
    {
        "title": "Finding Missing Values Using Mean",
        "body": '<h3>Using Mean Backwards</h3><p>If we know the mean and most of the values, we can find a missing value.</p><div class="concept-box"><strong>Sum = Mean \(\times\) Count</strong></div><h3>Example</h3><div class="worked-example"><p><strong>The mean of four numbers is 20. Three of the numbers are 18, 22, and 24. What is the fourth number?</strong></p><ul><li>Sum of all four = \(20 \times 4 = 80\)</li><li>Sum of three known = \(18 + 22 + 24 = 64\)</li><li>Fourth number = \(80 - 64 =\) <strong>16</strong></li></ul><p>Check: \((18 + 22 + 24 + 16) \div 4 = 80 \div 4 = 20\) ✓</p></div>'
    },
    {
        "title": "Real-World Application: Average Test Score",
        "body": '<h3>How Schools Use Mean</h3><p>Schools often use the mean to show how well a student or class is doing.</p><div class="worked-example"><p><strong>Sarah\'s maths scores are: 75, 80, 85, 90, 85. What is her average score?</strong></p><ul><li>Sum = \(75 + 80 + 85 + 90 + 85 = 415\)</li><li>Count = 5 tests</li><li>Mean = \(415 \div 5 =\) <strong>83</strong></li></ul><p>Sarah\'s average maths score is 83. This shows she is doing well in maths.</p></div><h3>Using Mean to Predict</h3><p>If a student\'s mean score is 83, we might expect their next test to be around 83. (Though it might be higher or lower!)</p>'
    }
]
